          "body": "The census ordinance of verses 11-16 interrupts the tabernacle-furniture sequence with what appears to be an administrative regulation but is actually a profound theological statement. When Israel is counted, each man's life is directly exposed to God's reckoning. The ransom (*kopher*) — a half-shekel of silver — must cover each *nephesh* (soul, v. 12), or plague breaks out. Why should counting generate plague? Because the act of numbering places each man under the direct gaze of the God who sees the iniquity that the numbered man carries. The ransom is not a temple tax; it is a soul-covering, a payment that says 'this life is acknowledged as forfeited and redeemed.' The absolute equality of the payment — rich and poor pay identically (v. 15) — is not egalitarian sentimentality but theological precision: before God's accounting there is no social rank, no purchasing of superior standing. Every soul costs the same because every soul stands in the same danger. The money collected funds the tent of meeting (v. 16), making atonement into infrastructure — the very place of meeting is sustained by the ransom of the souls who meet there."
